In article &lt;168@mirsa.inria.fr&gt; huitema@mirsa.inria.fr (Christian Huitema) writes:
...
&gt;large multinational companies like IBM, which maintain large internal nets:
&gt;for example our mail from "mirsa.inria.fr" (in Valbonne) to
&gt;"some.one@dec.com" (also in Valbonne, next door actually) crosses the ocean
&gt;twice, because the single recommanded gateway to ``DEC.COM'' lays somewhere
&gt;in the USA.
...
&gt;Christian Huitema

I see this as a mistake of DEC.

They should either set up a gateway for DEC.COM in France for you -- OR --

subdomain under DEC.COM (which they do to some extent) and tell the French
network about gateways to the subdomains of D.C which are in France.


One of the ideals of many people pushing domains is to have a notation
which doesn't imply routes.  Certainly an interesting goal and one that
would work -- at least for international organizations like DEC and IBM.

-- 
